the concrete does not shrink as it dries, leads to a reduction in the concrete density from 2.35 g/cm3 to
2.169 g/cm3.  Based on Table 9.1.12-7 of Engineering Compendium on Radiation Shielding edited by
R.G. Jaeger, et al, Vol.2, Shielding Materials, Springer-Verlag, 1975, total concrete shrinkage due to drying
can be about 1 part in 1000, so the density would only increase to about 2.169 x 1.001^3 = 2.176 g/cm3.
